04424nam a22007695i 9789814818124DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20182018si     fo  d z      eng d  a2018333879  a97898148181247 a10.1355/97898148181242doi  a(DE-B1597)526697  a(OCoLC)1078747441  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG00aDS570.M3bA58 2019 4aDS532.4.M35bA68 2019 7aSOC0200002bisacsh04a959.32231 aUnno, Anusorn, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10a“We Love Mr King” :bMalay Muslims of Southern Thailand in the Wake of the Unrest /cAnusorn Unno. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource (258 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Tables and Figures -- tAcknowledgements -- tMain “Dramatis Personae” (Alphabetically) -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1: Guba -- tChapter 2: Winds of Change -- tChapter 3: Subjectivities on the Rise -- tChapter 4: The Clashes -- tChapter 5: Living Lives with Multiple Subjectivities -- tChapter 6: Engaging with the Sovereigns -- tConclusion: Sovereignty in Crisis -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is an ethnography of the Malay Muslims of Guba, a pseudonymous village in Thailand’s Deep South, in the wake of the unrest that was primarily reinvigorated in 2004. It argues that the unrest is the effect of the way in which different forms of sovereignty converge around the residents of this region and the residents at the same time have cultivated themselves and obtained and enacted agency through the sovereigns. Rather than asking why the violence is increasing and who is behind it, like most scholarly works on the topic, it examines how different forms of sovereignty — ranging from the Thai state and the monarchy to Islamic religious movements, the insurgents and local strongmen — impose subjectivities on the residents, how they have converged in so doing and what tensions have followed, and how the residents have dealt with these tensions and cultivated themselves and obtained and enacted agency through the sovereigns. The phrase “We Love Mr King” or rao rak nay luang inscribed on the decorated, footed tray is one example of how the residents crafted themselves as royal subjects and enacted agency through the sovereign monarch.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIslam and politicszThailand, Southern. 0aMalays (Asian people)zThailand, SouthernxSocial conditions. 0aMuslimsxPolitical activityzThailand, Southern. 0aSovereigntyxReligious aspects. 4aIslamic Studies. 4aMinority Studies. 4aTerrorism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2018z978311071955008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060677540uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981481812440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789814818124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9789814818124.jpg  a978-3-11-060677-5  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  a978-3-11-071955-0  DG Plus eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK